[normal]Written [bold]evidence submitted by the NFU[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Summary[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]How best to improve UK (and EU) food security, including using resources more efficiently.[bold]a)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]F
[normal]armers need 
[normal]water[bold] to grow our food. Farmers rely on rainfall, public supply and abstraction from rivers and aquifers. Agriculture accounts for only 1% of total water abstracted nationally. Abstracted water is particularly important to the high value fruit and vegetable sector. 
[normal]E.g.
[normal] in the East of England, irrigated crops support a food and farming sector that provides 50,000 jobs and contributes £3 billion to the annual economy. 
[normal]F
[normal]armers and growers are already taking steps to improve water efficiency through on-farm storage, actively engaging in water abstractor groups, improving irrigation efficiency and installing rainwater harvesting.
[normal]b)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Fertiliser[bold] is an essential input ensuring that the productivity of crops is optimised. Phosphate and potash are both in finite supply in the long-term and whilst nitrogen can be manufactured, the process requires natural gas which in turn exposes the industry to fluctuations in supply and price in addition to the environmental and energy security impacts. Agriculture has reduced consumption of manufactured fertiliser in the last 20-30 years and farmers are recycling nutrients from both the agriculture sector and wider industry. The British Survey of Fertiliser Practices shows the declining trend in fertiliser nutrient applications between 1990 and 2012 with nitrogen applications in England and Wales down by 30%, phosphate applications down by 57% and potash down by 55%. Farmers are also improving use of organic fertiliser sources such as manures, biosolids, composts and digestates as alternative sources of nutrients and organic matter. Further skills and technology which optimise fertiliser usage, will help the industry to continue to improve nutrient use efficiency and sustainable cycling of nutrients, while ensuring that productivity is maintained or improved.
[normal]c)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The British farming industry is therefore acutely aware of the need to have a durable plan for 
[normal]energy[bold] security, yet the sector also has the potential to be a net exporter of energy. This is based upon a wide range of renewables including wind, solar and 
[normal]bioenergy (transport biofuels, biogas from anaerobic digestion of manures and crops, and biomass from wood, straw and perennial energy crops). The NFU strongly endorses land-based renewable energy which supports profitable agriculture, for example farmers own
[normal]ing
[normal] their own renewable energy assets or otherwise benefit
[normal]ing
[normal] from harnessing renewable energy resources. There are numerous opportunities to closely integrate renewables with both food production and the provision of biodiversity in agricultural landscapes.
