[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Ways of increasing self-sufficiency in products for which the UK has a comparative advantage[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]a)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Monitoring performance and ensuring efficiency gains[bold] - 
[normal]benchmarking data shows that by bringing the bottom 25% of farms in the UK up to the technical efficiency performance of the average, dairy output would increase by 9%,. Similarly, increasing the average to the top 25% would mean an extra 34% output.
[normal]b)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Confidence[bold] - 
[normal]the NFU believes that if dairy farmers had the confidence to invest (we suggest that on average farmers should be investing 3.5ppl per year in infrastructure) then improvements to efficiency and increasing output can be achieved.
[normal]c)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]International competitiveness[bold] – essential to
[normal] improve the margins on the farm and will encourage processors to invest in British milk fields.
[normal]d)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Building trust within the supply chain[bold] - identified as the most significant factor in the fresh produce sector, this could be addressed by retailers and processors supporting producers with clear and transparent pricing arrangements, longer term contracts, responsible promotional activities and support of British produce through in-store and online campaigns.
[normal]e)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Government departments facilitating growth of agriculture[bold] e.g. through planning decisions that recognise the need to produce more food; access to seasonal labour through managed agricultural workers schemes; decisions on plant protection product authorisations are based on practical, scientific evidence.
[normal]f)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Leadership and communication[bold] - it is important that Defra, AHDB and research organisations invest in and communicate research on sound farm management and new farming techniques. Similarly improving cow and bull genetics via genomic evaluation and further advances in feed conversion rates should be considered research priorities.
